<DOC><DOCNO> AP881027-0081 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 0910EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-CabotPrizes     10-27 0250</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Cabot Prizes,0257</SECOND><HEAD>4 Journalists Awarded 50th Annual Cabot Prizes</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Journalists from Argentina, Brazil, Peru and theUnited States have won the 50th annual Maria Moors Cabot Prizes forfostering understanding between the Americas, Columbia Universityannounced.   The winners announced Wednesday were Nicholas Clark Asheshov,editor of The Lima Times and The Andean Report of Lima, Peru; RobertCivita, creator and publisher of Veja of Sao Paulo, Brazil; StephenKinzer, foreign correspondent of The New York Times; andHermenegildo Sabat, staff cartoonist of Clarin in Buenos Aires,Argentina.   The awards, to be presented in ceremonies at the university thisevening, are given for distinguished contributions to inter-Americanunderstanding and freedom of information.   The winners receive gold medals and $1,000. Clarin and The NewYork Times are previous Cabot winners and will receive silver barsto be added to plaques the newspapers received earlier.   The Cabot prizes, the oldest international journalism awards,were established by Godfrey Lowell Cabot of Boston as a memorial tohis wife. Since 1939, 179 medals and 139 special citations have beengiven to journalists from 30 countries.   Asheshov is also the correspondent in Lima for The Sunday Times,the Daily Mail and The Daily Telegraph, all of London, and The MiamiHerald.   Civita is also president of the Brazilian Magazine PublishersAssociation.   Kinzer, a former aide to Democratic presidential candidateMichael Dukakis, has been correspondent for the Times in Nicaraguasince 1983. Sabat has been a cartoonist for Clarin since 1973.</TEXT></DOC>